# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bali
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bali/1962-asian-games] The **1962 Asian Games** (Indonesian: *Pesta Olahraga Asia 1962*) also known as the **4th Asian Games**, **IV Asiad**, and **Jakarta 1962**, were the fourth edition of pan-Asian multi-sport event sanctioned by the Asian Games Federation (AGF).
[src:bali/1962-asian-games] The games were held from 24 August to 4 September 1962, in Jakarta, Indonesia.
[src:bali/1962-asian-games] It was the first international multi-sport event hosted by the then-17-year-old Southeast Asian country.
[src:bali/1962-asian-games] This was the first of two Asian Games hosted by the city: the second was held in 2018, with Palembang as the co-host.
[src:bali/1962-asian-games] Israel and the Republic of China (ROC) were excluded from the Games, as in solidarity with People's Republic of China and fellow-Muslim majority countries in the Middle East, Indonesian immigration officials refused to issue entry visas for the Israeli and Taiwanese delegations.
[src:bali/1962-asian-games] It was a breach of the rules of the AGF, and Indonesia's own promise to invite all AGF members, including those with whom it had no diplomatic relations (Israel and Republic Of China).
[src:bali/1962-asian-games] As a result, Indonesia was suspended from the International Olympic Committee, and were subsequently excluded from the 1964 Summer Olympics.
[src:bali/1962-asian-games] Indonesia responded to this punishment by hosting the Games of the New Emerging Forces in 1963.
[src:bali/1962-asian-games] A total number of 1,460 athletes, coming from 17 countries, competed in this Asiad, where badminton made its debut.
[src:bali/1962-asian-games] On 23 May 1958, voting for the 1962 host took place in Tokyo, Japan, before the 1958 Asian Games.
[src:bali/1962-asian-games] The Asian Games Federation council voted 22–20 in favour of the Indonesian capital over Pakistani city of Karachi, the only other candidate.
[src:bali/1962-asian-games] Indonesia, only recently out from the shackles of colonialism, saw the fourth Asian games as its national pride.
[src:bali/1962-asian-games] Keeping this principle in mind, it acquired a loan of 12.5 million US dollars from Russia.
[src:bali/1962-asian-games] With the help of Russian experts, a giant stadium was built, which could accommodate 100,000 spectators.
[src:bali/1962-asian-games] Jakarta was renovated, and the efforts at renewal included complete removal of beggars and prostitutes.
[src:bali/1962-asian-games] Indonesian pride was so high at that time, that it did not invite Israel and Taiwan despite both being members of the Asian Games Federation [AGF].
[src:bali/1962-asian-games] All but three official sports were held inside or around the Gelora Bung Karno Sports Complex, temporarily called the Asian Games Complex.
[src:bali/1962-asian-games] The shooting event was held in Cibubur Shooting Range, in what is now lies within East Jakarta.
[src:bali/1962-asian-games] The weightlifting and wrestling events were held at Ikada Sports Hall, now demolished to make way for the National Monument.
[src:bali/1962-asian-games] The nearby Ikada Stadium was also used for football event, as well as Tebet football pitch, located southeast of the complex.
[src:bali/1962-asian-games] The archery demonstration event was held at Menteng Stadium.
[src:bali/1962-asian-games] While Weightlifting was in the program, the IWF withdrew recognition of the Asian Games competition after the Indonesian federation barred Taiwan and Israel from taking part.
[src:bali/1962-asian-games] Athletes from 15 nations competed at the Asian Games.
[src:bali/1962-asian-games] The top ten ranked NOCs at these Games are listed below.
[src:bali/1962-asian-games] The host nation, Indonesia, is highlighted.
[src:bali/1962-asian-games] In Indonesia, a television station TVRI was established by the Indonesian government to broadcast the games for the general public, which was the first in the country.
[src:bali/1962-asian-games] The station would become the main channel of TVRI network; and its first airdate, which coincides with the opening ceremony, become the network's founding date.
[src:bali/1999-indonesian-legislative-election] Early legislative elections were held in Indonesia on 7 June 1999.
[src:bali/1999-indonesian-legislative-election] They were the first elections since the fall of Suharto and end of the New Order, the first free elections in Indonesia since 1955, and the first and only free legislative election held in East Timor during Indonesian provincehood.
[src:bali/1999-indonesian-legislative-election] With the ending of restrictions on political activity following the fall of Suharto, a total of 48 parties contested the 462 seats up for election in the People's Representative Council.
[src:bali/1999-indonesian-legislative-election] A further 38 seats were reserved for members of the armed forces.
[src:bali/1999-indonesian-legislative-election] Under the New Order, only two political parties forcibly merged in 1973 – Indonesian Democratic Party (PDI) and United Development Party (PPP) – plus the functional group Golkar had been allowed to participate in elections.
[src:bali/1999-indonesian-legislative-election] With the start of the Reform Era, more than 100 new political parties emerged.
[src:bali/1999-indonesian-legislative-election] New elections were called for 1999 and 148 parties registered with the Ministry of Justice and Human Rights.
[src:bali/1999-indonesian-legislative-election] Of these, only 48 passed the selection process, overseen by intellectual Nurcholish Madjid.
[src:bali/1999-indonesian-legislative-election] The elections were to be overseen by an independent General Elections Commission (KPU) of 53 members, one from each party and five government representatives.
[src:bali/1999-indonesian-legislative-election] The system used was based on closed party-list proportional representation at the provincial level (in province-wide districts).
[src:bali/1999-indonesian-legislative-election] Within each province, parties were awarded seats in proportion to their share of the vote.
[src:bali/1999-indonesian-legislative-election] The East Java province had the most number of seats, with 82, while the lowest was in Bengkulu and East Timor with four each.
[src:bali/1999-indonesian-legislative-election] The official election campaign began on 19 May 1999 and ended on 4 June to allow two 'rest days' before the vote itself.
[src:bali/1999-indonesian-legislative-election] It was divided into three stages, with different parties being allowed to campaign on different days.
[src:bali/1999-indonesian-legislative-election] However, before the campaign, there was violence between supporters of rival parties.
[src:bali/1999-indonesian-legislative-election] Four people were killed in fighting between followers of the United Development Party (PPP) and the National Awakening Party (PKB) on 1 May and three more died in clashes between Golkar and Indonesian Democratic Party of Struggle (PDI-P) supporters on 11 May.
[src:bali/1999-indonesian-legislative-election] On the first day of the campaign there was a parade of party vehicles in Central Jakarta.
[src:bali/1999-indonesian-legislative-election] The Golkar float was attacked and damaged The traffic circle in front of Hotel Indonesia was a popular spot for rallies.
[src:bali/1999-indonesian-legislative-election] Meanwhile, there was an increase of people heading for Singapore to escape possible violence as polling day neared, with one newspaper reporting that more than 78,000 people had left.
[src:bali/1999-indonesian-legislative-election] As well as rallies, the major parties took out full-colour advertisements in newspapers.
[src:bali/1999-indonesian-legislative-election] Each party was also given air time TV for statements by lone spokespeople.
[src:bali/1999-indonesian-legislative-election] There were also ads in the newspapers urging people to use their vote.
[src:bali/1999-indonesian-legislative-election] In the final week, the main parties held huge rallies in the capital: the PKB on 1 June, the National Mandate Party (PAN) on 2 June, the PDI-P on 3 June and Golkar on 4 June, at which its supporters were attacked.
[src:bali/1999-indonesian-legislative-election] At one minute past midnight on 5 June, all party flags, banners and posters began to be removed as the campaign officially ended.
[src:bali/1999-indonesian-legislative-election] International observers continued to arrive to oversee the election, among them former US president Jimmy Carter.
[src:bali/1999-indonesian-legislative-election] In the last few days before the vote on 7 June, newspapers carried advertisements sponsored by the Indonesian Election Committee (PPI) explaining how to vote and urging people to do so.
[src:bali/1999-indonesian-legislative-election] On the day itself, polls opened at 8 am.
[src:bali/1999-indonesian-legislative-election] People cast their vote by piercing the party symbol on the ballot paper and then dipped a finger in indelible ink to prevent repeat voting.
[src:bali/1999-indonesian-legislative-election] When the votes were counted, each ballot paper was held up for onlookers to see.
[src:bali/1999-indonesian-legislative-election] There was independent monitoring down to the level of polling stations by Indonesians as well as by 100 observers and support staff from 23 counties led by Jimmy Carter.
[src:bali/1999-indonesian-legislative-election] On polling day, Carter said that it would have been extremely difficult to manipulate the election data because of the well-prepared information network and because the information was easy to access.
[src:bali/1999-indonesian-legislative-election] One way the public could access the latest results was by sending a short message service text to a specific number.
[src:bali/1999-indonesian-legislative-election] The sender then received information about provincial or party results.
[src:bali/1999-indonesian-legislative-election] On 9 June, Carter's team reported that although there had been "shortcomings" and allegations of financial abuses, they did not appear to have had a significant impact on the polling day activities.
[src:bali/1999-indonesian-legislative-election] The count was slow, with votes taking several weeks to count.
[src:bali/1999-indonesian-legislative-election] Before he left Indonesia, Carter expressed his concern about this.
[src:bali/1999-indonesian-legislative-election] At a meeting at the General Election Commission building on 26 June, only 22 of the 53 members of the commission were prepared to accept the result.
[src:bali/1999-indonesian-legislative-election] These comprised the representatives of 17 of the parties (with 93% of the vote between them) and the five government representatives.
[src:bali/1999-indonesian-legislative-election] Eventually, later that same day President Bacharuddin Jusuf Habibie in a live TV broadcast declared the results were valid.
[src:bali/1999-indonesian-legislative-election] The PDI-P, led by Megawati Sukarnoputri, had won the largest share of the vote with Golkar in second place.
[src:bali/1999-indonesian-legislative-election] The process of allocating seats in the People's Representative Council took several months with the PPI announcing the results on 1 September.
[src:bali/1999-indonesian-legislative-election] A total of 21 parties had won seats, with the PDI-P winning 153 and Golkar 120.
[src:bali/1999-indonesian-legislative-election] There were ten parties with only one seat each.
[src:bali/1999-indonesian-legislative-election] On 20 and 21 October 1999, about four months after the legislative elections, the People's Consultative Assembly elected the president and vice president of Indonesia for the 1999–2004 term.
[src:bali/1999-indonesian-legislative-election] Abdurrahman Wahid was elected president and Megawati Sukarnoputri as vice president.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] On 12 October 2002, terrorist attacks took place in the tourist district of Kuta on the Indonesian island of Bali.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] Bombings killed 202 people— 151 Westerners, 38 local Indonesians, 10 people from another 6 countries, and 3 unidentified victims—and injured a further 209, making it the worst terrorist act in Indonesia's history.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] Various members of Jemaah Islamiyah (also abbreviated JI), an Islamist group, were convicted in relation to the bombings, including three who were sentenced to death.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] The attack involved the detonation of three bombs: a bomb vest worn by a suicide bomber; a large car bomb, both of which were detonated in or near popular Kuta nightclubs; and a third, much smaller device detonated outside the United States consulate in Denpasar, causing only minor damage.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] On 9 November 2005, one of the top JI's bomb-makers, former Malaysian university lecturer Azahari Husin, was killed in a police raid on a house in Batu, East Java.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] Azahari was believed to be the technical mastermind behind the Bali bombings and several terrorist attacks in Indonesia during the early 2000s.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] On 9 November 2008, Amrozi bin Nurhasyim, Imam Samudra, and Mukhlas were executed by firing squad in the island prison of Nusakambangan.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] On 9 March 2010, Dulmatin, nicknamed "The Genius"—believed to have set off one of the Bali bombs with a mobile phone—was killed in a shootout with Indonesian police in Pamulang, South Tangerang.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] At 11:05 p.m. on 12 October 2002, a suicide bomber inside the nightclub *Paddy's Pub* (sometimes called *Paddy's Irish Bar* or *Paddy's Bar*) detonated an explosives vest, causing many patrons, with or without injuries, to flee into the street.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] Twenty seconds later, a powerful Mitsubishi van was driven into the club and detonated by another suicide bomber outside the *Sari Club*, a renowned open-air thatch-roof bar opposite *Paddy's Pub*.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] The bombing occurred during one of the year's busiest tourist periods in Kuta Beach, driven in part by many Australian sporting teams making their annual end-of-season holiday.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] Damage to the densely populated residential and commercial district was immense, destroying neighbouring buildings and shattering windows several blocks away.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] The car bomb explosion left a one-metre-deep (3.3 ft) crater.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] The local Sanglah Hospital was ill-equipped to deal with the scale of the disaster and was overwhelmed with the number of injured, particularly burn victims.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] So many people were injured by the explosion that some of them had to be placed in hotel pools near the explosion site to ease the pain of their burns.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] Many had to be flown great distances, to Darwin (1,800 km or 1,100 mi) and Perth (2,600 km or 1,600 mi), for specialist burn treatment.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] A comparatively small bomb exploded outside the U.S. consulate in Denpasar, causing minor injuries to one person and minimal property damage.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] It was reportedly packed with human excrement and is thought to have exploded shortly before the two Kuta bombs.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] The final death toll was 202, mainly comprising Western tourists and holiday-makers in their 20s and 30s who were in or near Paddy's Pub or the Sari Club, but also including many Balinese Indonesians working or living nearby, or simply passing by.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] Hundreds more people suffered horrific burns and other injuries.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] The largest group among those killed were Australian tourists, with 88 fatalities.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] On 14 October, the United Nations Security Council passed Resolution 1438 condemning the attack as a threat to international peace and security.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] There were many acts of individual heroism in the bombings' aftermath.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] Several of these received official recognition under Australia's honours and awards system, particularly in the Special Honours List for 2003.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] Natalie Goold initially escaped from Paddy's Bar after the bombings but then went back into the burning building, sustaining burns to her right arm and hand, to rescue her friend Nicole McLean, who had been heavily injured by the blasts.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] After asking two men for their shirts to use as tourniquets for McLean's wounds, Goold secured McLean's transportation to a local hospital and stayed with her during their medical evacuation to Australia.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] Robert Meredith and his group of friends were caught up in the bombing of the Sari Club; he was thrown onto his back and badly winded.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] Meredith would ultimately be left with several burns and cuts to his feet.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] Lauren Munro was also caught up in the Sari bombing, being rendered unconscious; when he came to, he pulled free an injured woman who had been trapped under roof beams, and carried her out of the building and over a wall of rubble.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] Munro helped several other people get over the same wall before re-entering the Sari Club and spending the next two hours carrying out many more injured people and helping to fight the fire.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] Ben Clohessy was also rendered unconscious by the blast that destroyed the Sari Club and also rescued or helped to rescue other survivors after regaining consciousness.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] Goold, Meredith, Munro, and Clohessy were all awarded the Star of Courage (SC) on 17 October 2003 for their respective actions.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] Awards of the Commendation for Brave Conduct were made to, among other people, Hanabeth Luke.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] Luke was in the Sari Club with her partner Marc Gajado at the time of the second bombing, with the explosion throwing her to the ground.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] After managing to escape the now-burning building by climbing through its collapsed roof using severed electrical wire, Luke began a search for Gajado, during which she came across a badly injured Tom Singer.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] Singer was lying close to a burning car and Luke believed that he would be engulfed in flames if he remained there.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] When Singer confirmed that he could not stand up independently, Luke helped him to his feet and supported him in walking away.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] Separately from her Commendation for Brave Conduct award, a photograph of Luke helping Singer was published in news media around the world in the days after the bombings.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] Kusitino 'Kossy' Halemai, a Wallis and Futuna-born Australian citizen who was managing the Bounty Hotel in Kuta at the time of the attacks, sheltered survivors in the immediate aftermath of the blasts.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] A makeshift triage area in the hotel's reception area was organised by Richard and Gilana Poore, with the couple also fielding phone calls from the media and from families trying to trace loved ones.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] After three days of this, the Poores flew to Richard's native New Zealand where they organised the collection of eighty boxes of medical supplies; they then returned to Bali with these supplies as well as two burns nurses.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] Halemai and the Poores were honoured with the Medal of the Order of Australia (OAM), with Gilana Poore's OAM being awarded on 26 January 2005, Halemai's OAM being awarded on 13 June 2005, and Richard Poore's OAM being awarded on 22 August 2005.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] James Parkinson, an emergency nurse, worked alongside Doctor Hogg from Wollongong in the Denpasar Sanglah Hospital running the trauma centre for the bombing victims.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] After he disappeared in Africa and Europe for three years, the Governor General's department finally tracked him down and awarded Parkinson the Medal of the Order of Australia in 2005.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] The Mitsubishi L300 van bomb was initially thought to have consisted of C4, a military grade plastic explosive which is difficult to obtain.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] However, investigators discovered the bomb was made from potassium chlorate, aluminium powder, and sulfur.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] For the Sari club bomb with the L300 van, the terrorists assembled 12 plastic filing cabinets filled with explosives.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] The cabinets, each containing a potassium chlorate, aluminum powder, sulfur mixture with a TNT booster, were connected by 150 metres (490 ft) of PETN-filled detonating cord.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] Ninety-four RDX electric detonators were fitted to the TNT.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] The total weight of the van bomb was 1,020 kilograms (2,250 lb).
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] The large, high-temperature blast damage produced by this mixture was similar to a thermobaric explosive, although the bombers may not have known this.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] The organization suspected of responsibility for the bombing was Jemaah Islamiyah, an Islamist group allegedly led by radical cleric Abu Bakar Bashir.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] The recording did not however claim responsibility for the Bali attack.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] Former FBI agent Ali Soufan confirmed in his book, *The Black Banners*, that al-Qaeda did in fact finance the attack.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] In addition, Riduan Isamuddin confessed that al-Qaeda had sent him US$30,000 to fund the bombings of the two nightclubs.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] Aris Munandar (aka Sheik Aris) is a Jemaah Islamiyah associate linked to Bashir.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] He is believed to have assisted the Bali bomber Amrozi in acquiring some of the explosives used in the Bali bombings.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] Philippine intelligence considers Munandar to be associated with Mohammad Abdullah Sughayer, a Saudi national Abu Sayyaf Group in southern Philippines.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] A report by the United States-Indonesia Society describes the arrest of Amrozi and other suspects.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] Indonesian authorities also believe more suspects remain at large.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] In 2005, Indonesian police arrested 24 additional people suspected of involvement in the Bali attacks and a 2003 bombing of the Marriott Hotel in Jakarta.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] On 12 October 2005, a story in Australian broadcaster SBS's documentary series *Dateline*, called "Inside Indonesia's War on Terrorism", argued that the Indonesian military or police may have been involved in executing the attack.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] On 13 June 2007, it was reported that Abu Dujana, who might have headed a terrorist cell in Bali, was captured.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] Just past midnight on 9 November 2008, the three convicted of carrying out the bombings (Imam Samudra, Amrozi Nurhasyim, and Ali Ghufron) were executed by a firing squad.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] Umar Patek was finally arrested in Abbottabad, Pakistan in early 2011.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] The U.S. government had offered a US$1 million reward for his arrest.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] Patek is a suspect in other bombings as well as the one in Bali.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] Another suspect named Zulkarnaen was finally arrested in Lampung on 10 December 2020.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] He was also stated to have orchestrated numerous Jemaah Islamiyah-related incidents in the past and been one of the executives of said terrorist group.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] In April 2003, Indonesian authorities charged Abu Bakar Bashir (also rendered "Ba'asyir"), the alleged spiritual leader of Jemaah Islamiyah, with treason.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] It was alleged that he tried to overthrow the government and establish an Islamic state.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] The specific charges against Bashir related to a series of church bombings on Christmas Eve in 2000, and to a plot to bomb United States and other Western interests in Singapore.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] He was initially not charged over the Bali attack, although he was frequently accused of being the instigator or inspirer of the attack.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] On 2 September, Bashir was acquitted of treason but convicted of lesser charges and sentenced to a prison term of four years.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] On 15 October 2004, he was arrested by the Indonesian authorities and charged with involvement in another bomb attack, which killed 14 people at the J.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] Marriott hotel in Jakarta on 5 August 2003.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] Secondary charges in this indictment accused him of involvement in the Bali bombing, the first time he faced charges in relation to this attack.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] On 3 March 2005, Bashir was found not guilty of the charges surrounding the 2003 bombing, but guilty of conspiracy over the 2002 attacks in Bali.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] He was sentenced to two and a half years imprisonment.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] The Australian, US, and many governments expressed its disappointment that the sentence was too short.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] In the outcome, Bashir was freed on 14 June 2006 having served less than 26 months for his conspiracy.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] On 21 December 2006, Bashir's conviction was overturned by Indonesia's Supreme Court.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] On 30 April 2003, the first charges related to the Bali bombings were made against Amrozi bin Haji Nurhasyim, known as Amrozi, for allegedly buying the explosives and the van used in the bombings.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] On 8 August, he was found guilty and sentenced to death.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] Another participant in the bombing, Imam Samudra, was sentenced to death on 10 September.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] Amrozi's brother, Ali Imron, who had expressed remorse for his part in the bombing, was sentenced to life imprisonment on 18 September.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] A fourth accused, Ali Ghufron, the brother-in-law of Noordin Mohammed Top was sentenced to death on 1 October.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] Ali Ghufron, alias Mukhlas, told police that he was the head of one of Jemaah Islamiyah's four cells and had ordered the Bali bombings.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] He also confessed that a fellow leader Riduan Isamuddin, known as Hambali, had provided the funds for the attacks.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] Another operative, Wan Min bin Wan Mat, revealed to police that he had given Mukhlas money, at Hambali's request and that he understood part of the money had come directly from al-Qaeda.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] As noted below, all three were executed on 9 November 2008.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] The Australian, US, and many other foreign governments expressed satisfaction with the speed and efficiency with which the Indonesian police and courts dealt with the bombings primary suspects, despite what they characterized as light sentences.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] All Australian jurisdictions abolished the death penalty more than 30 years ago, but a poll showed that 77% of Australians approved of the death sentence for Amrozi.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] The Australian government said it would not ask Indonesia to refrain from using the death penalty.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] On 11 August 2003, Riduan Isamuddin, generally known as Hambali, described as the operational chief of Jemaah Islamiyah was arrested in Ayutthaya, Thailand, the old capital one hour's drive north of Bangkok.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] He is in American custody in the Guantanamo Bay detention camp.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] On 23 July 2004, one of the convicted bombers, Maskur Abdul Kadir, successfully appealed his conviction.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] He had been tried under retroactive laws which were introduced after the bombing and which were employed to aid the prosecution of those involved in the attack.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] These laws were used by the prosecution instead of existing criminal laws as they allowed the death penalty to be imposed and lowered certain evidentiary restrictions.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] The highest court in Indonesia, the Constitutional Court, found by a margin of five to four that trying the terrorist suspects under these retroactive laws violated Article 28I(1) of the constitution [2].
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] The minority judges argued that international human rights documents such as the International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights allowed an exception to not applying retrospective legislation in the prosecution of crimes against humanity.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] The majority found that this argument was inconsistent with the text of Article 28I(1) which states that the rights listed there "cannot be limited under any circumstances".
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] Following this decision, charges related to the bombings against Idris, who had confessed to participating in the attacks to the police and court, were dismissed.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] The legal status of Kadir, Idris and others who might have their convictions quashed following the ruling on the retrospective law is unclear.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] The Constitutional Court is a relatively new body, created after the fall of Suharto, and this decision was one of the first to overrule the constitutionality of the government's application of a law.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] On 24 October 2008, Bali officials announced that three men convicted of carrying out the bombings would be executed by firing squad in November 2008.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] On 25 October 2008, Communications and Information Minister asked the Indonesian media to stop calling the three "heroes".
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] The Denpasar District Court, on 3 November, accepted a reprieve motion to reconsider the death sentences.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] Indonesia's Supreme Court denied previous petitions for judicial review amid the constitutional court's dismissal of the bombers' appeals.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] Denpasar court official Nengah Sanjaya said the 3-page appeal would be sent to a Cilacap, central Java court.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] But the Attorney General's office said on 1 November the execution was "very close".
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] Local chief prosecutor Muhammad Yamin said they would be "executed simultaneously" but at different locations.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] Amrozi, Imam Samudra and Ali Ghufron were executed by firing squad after midnight on 9 November 2008 (West Indonesian time).
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] In the final moment, there was no remorse or repentance, and they shouted *Allahu Akbar* ("God is great!").
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] Despite his carefree demeanor throughout his trial and incarceration, the Australian edition of *The Daily Telegraph* reported Amrozi was pale-faced and shaking in the moments before his execution.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] For burial, Mukhlas and Amrozi's bodies were flown by helicopter to Tenggulun, Lamongan, East Java, while Imam Samudra's body was flown to Serang, Banten, amid "welcome martyrs" banner displayed at the cemetery.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] The execution caused high tension and sparked clashes in Tenggulun between hundreds of police and supporters.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] Indonesian singer and TV presenter Dorce Gamalama attended the funeral of Imam Samudra.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] After praying with the crowd, she spent half an hour in the house of the executed man and spoke with his mother.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] On leaving she was quoted as saying "I'm certain he's gone to heaven".
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] Ma'ruf Amin, deputy chairman of the Indonesian Ulema Council, the chief body for Islamic clerics in Indonesia said of the men: "They did not die a holy death.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] After the execution, several countries issued a travel warning to Indonesia due to safety issues.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] The travel warning resulted in cancellation of Barbadian singer concert Rihanna that was scheduled to be held at Istora Gelora Bung Karno on 14 November 2008, five days after the execution.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] The concert was originally rescheduled to 12 February 2009, but was cancelled again due to Chris Brown assault on Rihanna incident. as a result, she become the first artist to cancel the concert at Istora after 48 years of operational.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] A permanent memorial was built on the site of the destroyed Paddy's Pub on Legian Street.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] (A new bar, named "Paddy's: Reloaded", was reopened further along Legian Street).
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] The memorial is made of intricately carved stone, set with a large marble plaque, which bears the names and nationalities of each of those killed.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] It is flanked by the national flags of the victims.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] The monument is well-maintained and illuminated at night.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] The memorial was dedicated on 12 October 2004, the second anniversary of the attack.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] The dedication included a Balinese Hindu ceremony and the opportunity for mourners to lay flowers and other offerings.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] The Australian ambassador and Indonesian officials attended the ceremony.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] The Balinese mark their commitment in a nine-day-long event.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] After major cleansing ceremonies, establishing a memorial for the lost lives, and paying respect to those who left loved ones behind, the people of Kuta look forward to restoring Bali's image through an event named "Kuta Karnival — A Celebration of Life".
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] The community event consists of traditional art performances such as Balinese Sunset Dances, sports on the beach as well as in the water for young and old plus rows and rows of culinary displays along the one kilometre of sandy beach.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] In line with the return of tourism to Kuta, Kuta Karnival has grown into a tourism promotional event with major coverage from television and newspapers from across the globe.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] Tourists and locals alike, more than ninety thousand people, participate in the numerous events year after year.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] Further bombings in Bali in 2005 did not reduce the Kuta community's determination to carry out this annual event.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] Kuta Karnival is conducted to commemorate and give respect to the victims of human violence and show the world the true spirit of local community survival despite terrorism attacks.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] On 12 October 2010, Australian and Indonesian survivors of the 2002 bombings attended a solemn commemoration service to mark the eighth anniversary of the devastating attacks.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] In Lincoln Square on the western side of Swanston Street in Carlton, Melbourne, is a memorial representing the 88 Australians who died in the bombings, and notably the 22 from Victoria.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] There are 88 jets in the fountain; at night, there are lights representing all those who died.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] The fountain shuts off and becomes a reflecting pool on 12 October each year.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] This was one of the very few fountains allowed to operate during the drought in 2007.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] Christine Anu sang The Lighthouse by toxtwo at the opening ceremony.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] One Melburnian survivor of the bombings was North Melbourne AFL player Jason McCartney.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] He suffered second-degree burns to over 50% of his body while helping carry others to safety and nearly died during surgery after being transported back to Melbourne.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] 's television call of McCartney's return after the bombings (North Melbourne vs.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] After a long rehabilitation process, McCartney returned for a single AFL match: North Melbourne vs.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] Richmond at Docklands Stadium in Melbourne on 6 June 2003.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] He wore compression garments and protective gloves as well as the numbers "88" and "202" on his jersey, signifying the Australian and total numbers of victims, respectively, while many in the crowd held up signs saying "Bali 88/202".
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] McCartney helped North Melbourne to a narrow win before announcing his retirement at the end of the game, and his comeback has been cited as one of the AFL's most inspirational stories.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] A memorial which lists the victims of the bombings from Western Australia was opened on the first anniversary, and is situated on the ridge of Mount Eliza in Kings Park, overlooking the city.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] The memorial is specifically designed to frame the sun's rays at dawn on 12 October each year and faces in the exact direction of Bali.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] Due to the construction of EQ West in Elizabeth Quay, sunlight no longer reaches the memorial.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] An Indonesian-style stone memorial is situated in Allambe Memorial Park at Nerang.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] A bronze plaque lists the names of the 88 Australians who died in the bombings.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] An annual twilight service is held at the site of the memorial on each anniversary of the Bali bombings.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] On the northern side of Coogee Beach a memorial to the Bali bombing victims comprises three interlocking bronze shapes that have an abstract resemblance to three bowed figures supporting each other.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] There are also some graffiti memorials in memory of the dead.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] A memorial to seven residents of Sutherland Shire who were victims is at Cronulla.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] Called *The Seed*, the work is based on the seed and foliage of the *Banksia robur*, a native plant indigenous to the Shire.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] This sculpture of pink sandstone is the centrepiece of the memorial.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] It is set in a black granite pond located in 'Peryman Place' not far from North Cronulla Beach, frequented by many of the seven victims and their families.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] Two plaques are set into the granite surrounding the pond.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] The plaques carry the victims' photos, names, and ages; and also details of the event, the design's symbolism, its dedication, and a poem written by the families of the victims.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] The work is by sculptor Chris Bennetts and Ishi Buki Sandstone Sculpture.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] South of Sydney, in the town of Ulladulla, a large youth centre was built as a memorial to Craig Dunn and Danny Lewis, two local victims of the bombings.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] Money was raised through the Dunn & Lewis Youth Development Foundation.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] A granite cube serves as a memorial in the Eastern Formal Gardens of Parliament House.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] On the fourth anniversary of the bombings the Prince of Wales and Duchess of Cornwall (now Charles III and Queen Camilla) unveiled a memorial in London, at the rear of the Foreign and Commonwealth Office Main Building, facing St.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] The memorial consists of a 1.5-metre marble globe, to represent that people from 21 countries were killed, and has 202 doves carved into it.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] The names of all 202 victims are on a curved stone wall behind the globe.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] It is the work of the artist Gary Breeze and the sculptor Martin Cook.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] There is a small stone memorial to the 28 British nationals who died, in the small country park of Ratby Burroughs in Leicestershire.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] In 2005, two marble wall placards were unveiled at Hong Kong Football Club in memory of the members of the club who were killed in the bombings (including Jake Young).
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] The service is attended by survivors of the 2002 rugby tour to Bali, friends and family of those who lost their lives, as well as current and past players of the club.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] The SCC also maintains a permanent memorial to the players it lost inside the club's main lounge.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] A remembrance garden was constructed at the International School Ho Chi Minh City commemorating teachers from that school who were killed in the bombings.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] In 2006, *Long Road to Heaven*, an Indonesian feature film about the bombings, was released by Kalyana Shira Films.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] The film was directed by Enison Sinaro and written by Wong Wai Leng and Andy Logam-Tan.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] It stars Raelee Hill, Mirrah Foulkes, Alex Komang, Surya Saputra, John O' Hare, Sarah Treleaven, and Joshua Pandelaki.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] It tells the story during three different times: the planning a few months before the bombing, its execution in 2002, and the trials in 2003 through the viewpoints of both the victims and the bombers.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] The story is not chronologically linear, starting with the explosion and then moving from time to time so as all three plots are culminated one after the other.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] At the beginning of each scene, subtitles tell the date and location of the scene.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] A comic book about the first Bali bombing was launched to promote peace and discourage radicalism and terrorism in Indonesia.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] A *Seconds from Disaster* episode, "Bali Bombings", was a documentary telling the story of what happened, and looking at what happened after the incident.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] A *Zero Hour* documentary depicts the disaster.
[src:bali/2002-bali-bombing] In 2022 (20 years after the incident), the Australian-Indonesian historical drama *Bali 2002*, aired on Stan and Nine Network.
[src:bali/2005-bali-bombing] Terrorist attacks occurred on 1 October 2005 in Bali, Indonesia.
[src:bali/2005-bali-bombing] Bombs were detonated at two sites in Jimbaran Beach resort and in Kuta 30 km (19 mi) away, both in south Bali.
[src:bali/2005-bali-bombing] The attacks killed 20 people and injured more than 100 others.
[src:bali/2005-bali-bombing] The Indonesian national news agency, ANTARA, reported that the first two explosions occurred at 6:50 p.m. local time, near a Jimbaran food court and the third at 7:00 pm. in Kuta Town Square.
[src:bali/2005-bali-bombing] Other reports claim that the blasts occurred at around 7:15 p.m.
[src:bali/2005-bali-bombing] One of the blasts struck Raja's Restaurant at the Kuta Square shopping mall in central Kuta.
[src:bali/2005-bali-bombing] Another two bombs exploded at warungs along the Jimbaran beach, one of which was near the Four Seasons Hotel.
[src:bali/2005-bali-bombing] These areas are generally popular with Western tourists.
[src:bali/2005-bali-bombing] Police later said they had found three unexploded bombs in Jimbaran.
[src:bali/2005-bali-bombing] They had apparently failed to go off after the security forces hastily shut down the island's mobile telephone network following the first blasts.
[src:bali/2005-bali-bombing] According to Indonesia's head of counter-terrorism, Major General Ansyaad Mbai, early evidence indicates that the attacks were carried out by at least three suicide bombers in a similar fashion to the 2002 bombings.
[src:bali/2005-bali-bombing] The remnants of backpacks and excessively mutilated bodies are believed to be evidence of suicide bombings.
[src:bali/2005-bali-bombing] There remains also a possibility that backpacks were hidden inside the target restaurants before detonation.
[src:bali/2005-bali-bombing] Australian Federal Police Commissioner Mick Keelty said that the bombs used appear to have differed from previous blasts in that most deaths and injuries had been inflicted by shrapnel, rather than chemical explosion.
[src:bali/2005-bali-bombing] A medical officer's x-rays showed foreign objects described as "pellets" in many victims' bodies and a victim reported ball bearings lodged in her back.
[src:bali/2005-bali-bombing] The bombings occurred the same day that Indonesia cut its fuel subsidies resulting in gas prices rising by 675% and just two days before the start of the Muslim holy month of Ramadan and 11 days before the third anniversary of the 2002 Bali bombings.
[src:bali/2005-bali-bombing] The attack came during the school holiday period in some states of Australia, when an estimated 7,500 Australians are believed to have been visiting Bali.
[src:bali/2005-bali-bombing] The latest report cites 20 dead and between 101 and 129 injured.
[src:bali/2005-bali-bombing] Some earlier reports put the number of fatalities at between 26 and 36 people, but those figures have since been lowered.
[src:bali/2005-bali-bombing] Among those killed were 15 Indonesians, 4 Australians, and a Japanese national, not counting the 3 assassins.
[src:bali/2005-bali-bombing] The wounded included many Indonesians, mostly Hindus while the rest were 19 Australians, 8 South Koreans, 6 Americans, 4 Japanese, 3 Canadians and 1 Briton.
[src:bali/2005-bali-bombing] Most of the casualties were sent to Bali's Sanglah General Hospital, and mostly treated for injuries caused by broken glass.
[src:bali/2005-bali-bombing] Others were sent to Griya Asih Hospital.
[src:bali/2005-bali-bombing] As in the 2002 bombings, some of the injured, primarily foreign nationals, were evacuated to medical facilities in Australia and Singapore.
[src:bali/2005-bali-bombing] The less seriously injured were evacuated to Singapore, while other casualties, among them Australians, Japanese and an Indonesian, were evacuated to treatment in Darwin, Australia aboard a Royal Australian Air Force C-130 Hercules.
[src:bali/2005-bali-bombing] Indonesian authorities were expecting such an event, after the Indonesian president warned of more bombings within the country, and the Australian Department of Foreign Affairs (DFAT) had issued warnings two days before the event.
[src:bali/2005-bali-bombing] However, the Australian government claimed that it received no specific prior warning of a terrorist attack being imminent in Bali.
[src:bali/2005-bali-bombing] Minister Downer also played down any knowledge of specific signs of the potential event, despite the DFAT warning on the last day of September.
[src:bali/2005-bali-bombing] DFAT warned Australians against non-essential travel to Indonesia since before the 2002 attacks – a warning still in effect.
[src:bali/2005-bali-bombing] The department advises travellers against congregating in areas popular with Western tourists.
[src:bali/2005-bali-bombing] In May 2005, the US State Department issued a travel warning against non-essential trips to Indonesia.
[src:bali/2005-bali-bombing] The travel warning was last updated 9 January 2007.
[src:bali/2005-bali-bombing] A Philippine security official said that for months intelligence officials in Southeast Asia had received information that Jemaah Islamiyah was orchestrating a major strike, possibly in the Philippines or Indonesia, but were unable to uncover the plot's details in time to prevent it.
[src:bali/2005-bali-bombing] Although a link to JI has not been confirmed, the bombings were quickly condemned as terrorist attacks by the authorities.
[src:bali/2005-bali-bombing] Police Major General Ansyaad Mbai, a top Indonesian anti-terrorism official, told the Associated Press that the bombings "were clearly the work of terrorists".
[src:bali/2005-bali-bombing] Major General Mbai identified Malaysian men, already wanted in connection to previous bombings in Indonesia, as the suspected masterminds of the attacks.
[src:bali/2005-bali-bombing] The chief suspect was Azahari Husin, a member of JI who was an engineering expert and former academic with a doctorate from University of Reading (late 1980s).
[src:bali/2005-bali-bombing] Husin was nicknamed the "Demolition Man" and was thought to have collaborated with the second suspect: Noordin Mohammed Top, a bomb maker whose wife was sentenced to three years in prison for harbouring him.
[src:bali/2005-bali-bombing] Azahari was killed in a police raid on 9 November 2005 at Batu, East Java, while Noordin "has been killed after a lengthy and violent siege, Indonesia's police chief said" by "heavily armed counter-terrorism police" on 17 September 2009 at Surakarta, Central Java.
[src:bali/2005-bali-bombing] Motivations for the bombings remain unclear.
[src:bali/2005-bali-bombing] Some, such as the Australian Prime Minister, have suggested the attacks were intended to undermine Indonesia's moderate democratic government.
[src:bali/2005-bali-bombing] Moreover, media organisations have suggested that the attack was planned to correspond with massive fuel price increases in Indonesia, so as to maximise economic and political damage.
[src:bali/2005-bali-bombing] She suggested Bali was selected as the site of the attacks because there was less chance of Indonesian gangsters being killed, and there was "a chance of getting a few foreigners".
[src:bali/2005-bali-bombing] Following the attacks Abu Bakar Bashir, who is alleged to be JI's spiritual leader, released a statement from his prison cell, condemning the attack.
[src:bali/2005-bali-bombing] But he added that the bombings were a sign of God's displeasure with the Indonesian government.
[src:bali/2005-bali-bombing] They all had a good intention, that is, Jihad in Allah’s way, the aim of the jihad is to look for blessing from Allah.
[src:bali/2005-bali-bombing] They are right that America is the proper target because America fights Islam.
[src:bali/2005-bali-bombing] Indonesian police believed that three suicide bombers carried out the bombings.
[src:bali/2005-bali-bombing] A presidential spokesman Dino Djalal said that the police found a total of "six legs and three heads but no middle bodies, and that's the strong sign of suicide bombers." Photos of the three heads were published in The Jakarta Post on Monday, 3 October 2005.
[src:bali/2005-bali-bombing] Initially, there were conflicting reports on the number of bombs; but later, the police confirmed only three bombs.
[src:bali/2005-bali-bombing] An amateur video capturing the scene at the restaurant in Kuta showed one bomber with a backpack walking inside just seconds before a huge explosion.
[src:bali/2005-bali-bombing] On the following Monday, on 3 October 2005, the police issued an appeal to the public for help identifying the suspected suicide bombers whose dismembered remains were found at the scene.
[src:bali/2005-bali-bombing] Photos of the dead suspects were later distributed widely and a hotline was set up to receive tips.
[src:bali/2005-bali-bombing] According to Banten Police Chief Senior Commissioner Badrodin Haiti, the Indonesian police are seeking five members of a ring led by Imam Samudra, who has been sentenced to death for his role in the 2002 Bali bombings.
[src:bali/2005-bali-bombing] Three of the five men had already served jail sentences for holding explosives belonging to Samudra.
[src:bali/2005-bali-bombing] They were under police surveillance but had disappeared from their homes.
[src:bali/2005-bali-bombing] On 9 October 2005, police in Bali arrested a man, identified by the initials HS, who was allegedly a former roommate of one of the suicide bombers.
[src:bali/2005-bali-bombing] According to Indonesian police, in 2005, a corrupt prison warden at the Kerobokan prison smuggled a laptop inside for Imam Samudra, the leader of the terrorist group involved in the first Bali bombing.
[src:bali/2005-bali-bombing] He then used the laptop and a wireless connection to chat with other terrorist suspects.
[src:bali/2007-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The **2007 United Nations Climate Change Conference** took place at the Bali International Conference Centre, Nusa Dua, Bali, Indonesia, from 3 to 15 December 2007.
[src:bali/2007-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Representatives from over 180 countries attended, along with observers from intergovernmental and non-governmental organizations.
[src:bali/2007-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Negotiations on a successor to the Kyoto Protocol dominated the conference.
[src:bali/2007-united-nations-climate-change-conference] A meeting of environment ministers and experts held in June had called for the conference to agree on a roadmap, timetable, and "concrete steps for the negotiations" with the aim of reaching an agreement by 2009.
[src:bali/2007-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Initial EU proposals called for global emissions to peak within 10 to 15 years and decline to "well below half" of 2000 levels by 2050, with developed countries reducing emissions 20–40% below 1990 levels by 2020.
[src:bali/2007-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The United States strongly opposed these targets, at times backed by Japan, Canada, Australia, and Russia.
[src:bali/2007-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The resulting compromise mandated "deep cuts in global emissions" with references to the IPCC's Fourth Assessment Report.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Bali is the only Hindu-majority province in Indonesia, with 86.40% of the population adhering to Balinese Hinduism.
[src:bali/bali-p01] It is renowned for its highly developed arts, including traditional and modern dance, sculpture, painting, leather, metalworking, and music.
[src:bali/bali-p01] The Indonesian International Film Festival is held every year in Bali.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Other international events that have been held in Bali include Miss World 2013, the 2018 Annual Meetings of the International Monetary Fund and the World Bank Group, and the 2022 G20 summit.
[src:bali/bali-p01] In March 2017, Tripadvisor named Bali as the world's top destination in its Traveler's Choice award, which it earned once again in January 2021 and 2026.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Bali is part of the Coral Triangle, an area with high diversity of marine species, mainly fish and turtles.
[src:bali/bali-p01] In this area alone, over 500 reef-building coral species can be found.
[src:bali/bali-p01] For comparison, this is about seven times as many as in the entire Caribbean.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Bali is the home of the Subak irrigation system, a UNESCO World Heritage Site.
[src:bali/bali-p01] It is also home to a unified confederation of kingdoms composed of 10 traditional royal Balinese houses, each house ruling a specific geographic area.
[src:bali/bali-p01] The confederation is the successor of the Bali Kingdom.
[src:bali/bali-p01] The royal houses, which originated before Dutch colonisation, are not recognised by the government of Indonesia.
[src:bali/bali-p01] The name *Bali* is attested in ancient Balinese inscriptions as part of the compound *Vāli-dvīpa* (or *Wāli-dvīpa*), where Sanskrit *dvīpa* (Sanskrit: द्वीप) means "island".
[src:bali/bali-p01] One of the earliest attestations of *Vāli-dvīpa* occurs in the Belanjong (Blanjong) pillar inscription, dated to Saka year 835 / Phalguna month, under King Sri Kesari Warmadewa (c.
[src:bali/bali-p01] The precise meaning of the element *Vāli* in *Vāli-dvīpa* is not certain.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Bali was inhabited around 2000 BC by Austronesian peoples who migrated originally from the island of Taiwan to Southeast Asia and Oceania through Maritime Southeast Asia.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Culturally and linguistically, the Balinese are closely related to the people of the Indonesian archipelago, Malaysia, Brunei, the Philippines, and Oceania.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Stone tools dating from this time have been found near the village of Cekik in the island's west.
[src:bali/bali-p01] In ancient Bali, nine Hindu sects existed: the Pasupata, Bhairawa, Siwa Shidanta, Vaishnava, Bodha, Brahma, Resi, Sora, and Ganapatya.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Each sect revered a specific deity as its personal Godhead.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Inscriptions from 896 and 911 do not mention a king until 914, when Sri Kesarivarma, a contemporary of the Kesari dynasty in the Kalinga Kingdom of ancient India, is mentioned.
[src:bali/bali-p01] They also reveal an independent Bali, with a distinct dialect, being influenced by the Sanskrit and Pali languages, where Buddhism and Shaivism were practiced simultaneously.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Mpu Sindok's great-granddaughter, Mahendradatta (Gunapriyadharmapatni), married the Bali king Udayana Warmadewa (Dharmodayanavarmadeva) around 989, giving birth to Airlangga around 1001.
[src:bali/bali-p01] This marriage also brought more Hinduism and Javanese culture to Bali.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Princess Sakalendukirana appeared in 1098.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Suradhipa reigned from 1115 to 1119, and Jayasakti from 1146 until 1150.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Jayapangus appears on inscriptions between 1178 and 1181, while Adikuntiketana and his son Paramesvara appear in 1204.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Balinese culture was strongly influenced by Indian, Chinese, and particularly Kalinga Hindu culture, beginning around the 1st century AD.
[src:bali/bali-p01] The name *Bali dwipa* ("Bali island") has been discovered from various inscriptions, including the Blanjong pillar inscription written by Sri Kesari Warmadewa in 914 AD, and mentioning **Walidwipa**.
[src:bali/bali-p01] It was during this time that the people developed their complex irrigation system, *subak,* to grow rice in wet-field cultivation.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Some religious and cultural traditions still practiced today can be traced to this period.
[src:bali/bali-p01] The Hindu-Buddhist Majapahit Empire (1293–1520 AD) on eastern Java founded a Balinese colony in 1343.
[src:bali/bali-p01] The uncle of Hayam Wuruk is mentioned in the charters of 1384–86.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Mass Javanese immigration to Bali occurred in the next century when the Majapahit Empire fell in 1520.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Bali's government then became an independent collection of Hindu kingdoms, which led to a Balinese national identity and major enhancements in culture, arts, and economy.
[src:bali/bali-p01] The nation with various kingdoms became independent for up to 386 years until 1906, when the Dutch subjugated and repulsed the natives for economic control and took it over.
[src:bali/bali-p01] The first known European contact with Bali is thought to have been made in 1512, when a Portuguese expedition led by Antonio Abreu and Francisco Serrão sighted its northern shores.
[src:bali/bali-p01] It was the first expedition of a series of bi-annual fleets to the Moluccas, which, throughout the 16th century, travelled along the coasts of the Sunda Islands.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Bali was also mapped in 1512, in the chart of Francisco Rodrigues, aboard the expedition.
[src:bali/bali-p01] In 1585, a ship foundered off the Bukit Peninsula and left a few Portuguese in the service of Dewa Agung.
[src:bali/bali-p01] In 1597, the Dutch merchant-explorer Cornelis de Houtman arrived at Bali, and the Dutch East India Company was established in 1602.
[src:bali/bali-p01] The Dutch government expanded its control across the Indonesian archipelago during the second half of the 19th century.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Dutch political and economic control over Bali began in the 1840s on the island's north coast when the Dutch pitted various competing Balinese realms against each other.
[src:bali/bali-p01] In the late 1890s, struggles between Balinese kingdoms on the island's south were exploited by the Dutch to increase their control.
[src:bali/bali-p01] In June 1860, the famous Welsh naturalist, Alfred Russel Wallace, travelled to Bali from Singapore, landing at Buleleng on the north coast of the island.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Wallace's trip to Bali was instrumental in helping him devise his Wallace Line theory.
[src:bali/bali-p01] The Wallace Line is a faunal boundary that runs through the strait between Bali and Lombok.
[src:bali/bali-p01] The Dutch mounted large naval and ground assaults at the Sanur region in 1906 and were met by the thousands of members of the royal family and their followers, who, rather than yield to the superior Dutch force, committed ritual suicide (*puputan*) to avoid the humiliation of surrender.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Despite Dutch demands for surrender, an estimated 200 Balinese killed themselves rather than surrender.
[src:bali/bali-p01] In the Dutch intervention in Bali, a similar mass suicide occurred in the face of a Dutch assault in Klungkung.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Afterward, the Dutch governors exercised administrative control over the island, but local control over religion and culture generally remained intact.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Dutch rule over Bali came later and was never as well established as in other parts of Indonesia, such as Java and Maluku.
[src:bali/bali-p01] In the 1930s, anthropologists Margaret Mead and Gregory Bateson, artists Miguel Covarrubias and Walter Spies, and musicologist Colin McPhee all spent time here.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Their accounts of the island and its peoples created a Western image of Bali as "an enchanted land of aesthetes at peace with themselves and nature".
[src:bali/bali-p01] Soon after, Western tourists began to visit the island.
[src:bali/bali-p01] The film, which mostly consisted of scenes of topless Balinese women, was a great success in 1932, and was perhaps the main catalyst for the popularity of Bali among tourists.
[src:bali/bali-p01] The Dutch also dedicated significant efforts to implement *Baliseering* (lit.
[src:bali/bali-p01] 'Balinization') politics to maintain traditions on the island, as well as preventing the Islamization of the Islamic sultanates from Java and banning Christian missionaries' activities.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Imperial Japan occupied Bali during World War II.
[src:bali/bali-p01] It was not originally a target in their Netherlands East Indies Campaign; however, as the airfields on Borneo were inoperative due to heavy rains, the Imperial Japanese Army decided to occupy Bali, which did not suffer from comparable weather.
[src:bali/bali-p01] The island had no regular Royal Netherlands East Indies Army (KNIL) troops.
[src:bali/bali-p01] There was only a Native Auxiliary Corps *Prajoda* (Korps Prajoda) consisting of about 600 native soldiers and several Dutch KNIL officers under the command of KNIL Lieutenant Colonel W.P.
[src:bali/bali-p01] On 19 February 1942, the Japanese forces landed near the town of Sanoer (Sanur) and the island was quickly captured.
[src:bali/bali-p01] During the Japanese occupation, a Balinese military officer, I Gusti Ngurah Rai, formed a Balinese 'freedom army'.
[src:bali/bali-p01] The harsh treatment of the Balinese by the Japanese occupation forces fomented more resentment than the former Dutch colonial rulers.
[src:bali/bali-p01] In 1945, Bali was liberated by the British 5th Infantry Division under the command of Major-General Robert Mansergh, who took the Japanese surrender.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Once Japanese forces had been repatriated, the island was handed over to the Dutch the following year.
[src:bali/bali-p01] In 1946, the Dutch constituted Bali as one of the 13 administrative districts of the newly proclaimed State of East Indonesia, a rival state to the Republic of Indonesia, which was proclaimed and headed by Sukarno and Hatta.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Bali was included in the "Republic of the United States of Indonesia" when the Netherlands recognised Indonesian independence on 29 December 1949.
[src:bali/bali-p01] The first governor of Bali, Anak Agung Bagus Suteja, was appointed by President Sukarno in 1958, when Bali became a province.
[src:bali/bali-p01] The 1963 eruption of Mount Agung killed thousands, created economic havoc, and forced many displaced Balinese to be transmigrated to other parts of Indonesia.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Mirroring the widening of social divisions across Indonesia in the 1950s and early 1960s, Bali saw conflict between supporters of the traditional caste system and those rejecting this system.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Politically, the opposition was represented by supporters of the Indonesian Communist Party (PKI) and the Indonesian Nationalist Party (PNI), with tensions and ill-feeling further increased by the PKI's land reform programmes.
[src:bali/bali-p01] A purported coup attempt in Jakarta was averted by forces led by General Suharto.
[src:bali/bali-p01] The army became the dominant power as it instigated a violent anti-communist purge backed by Western powers, in which the army blamed the PKI for the coup.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Most estimates suggest that at least 500,000 people were killed across Indonesia, with an estimated 80,000 killed in Bali, equivalent to 5% of the island's population.
[src:bali/bali-p01] With no Islamic forces involved as in Java and Sumatra, upper-caste PNI landlords led the extermination of PKI members.
[src:bali/bali-p01] As a result of the 1965–66 massacres, Suharto was able to manoeuvre Sukarno out of the presidency.
[src:bali/bali-p01] His "New Order" government re-established relations with Western countries.
[src:bali/bali-p01] The pre-war Bali, as "paradise," was revived in a modern form.
[src:bali/bali-p01] The resulting large growth in tourism has led to a dramatic increase in Balinese standards of living and significant foreign exchange earned for the country.
[src:bali/bali-p01] A bombing in 2002 by militant Islamists in the tourist area of Kuta killed 202 people, mostly foreigners.
[src:bali/bali-p01] This attack, and another in 2005, severely reduced tourism, producing much economic hardship on the island.
[src:bali/bali-p01] On 9 July 2008, for the first time in Bali's history, the election for governor and vice governor of Bali was democratically elected by the people of Bali directly.
[src:bali/bali-p01] On 27 November 2017, Mount Agung erupted five times, causing the evacuation of thousands, disrupting air travel, and causing much environmental damage.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Further eruptions also occurred between 2018 and 2019.
[src:bali/bali-p01] On 15–16 November 2022, with the 2022 G20 Bali summit, the seventeenth meeting of the Group of Twenty (G20) was held in Nusa Dua.
[src:bali/bali-p01] The island of Bali lies 3.2 km (2.0 mi) east of Java, and is approximately 8 degrees south of the equator.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Bali and Java are separated by the Bali Strait.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Its population density was roughly 798 people/km2 (2,070 people/mi2) in mid 2024.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Bali's central mountains include several peaks over 2,000 metres (6,600 feet) in elevation and active volcanoes such as Mount Batur.
[src:bali/bali-p01] The highest is Mount Agung (3,031 m; 9,944 ft), known as the "mother mountain", which is an active volcano rated as one of the world's most likely sites for a massive eruption within the next 100 years.
[src:bali/bali-p01] In late 2017, Mount Agung started erupting and large numbers of people were evacuated, temporarily closing the island's airport.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Mountains range from centre to the eastern side, with Mount Agung the easternmost peak.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Bali's volcanic nature has contributed to its exceptional fertility, and its tall mountain ranges provide the high rainfall that supports the highly productive agricultural sector.
[src:bali/bali-p01] South of the mountains is a broad, steadily descending area where most of Bali's large rice crop is grown.
[src:bali/bali-p01] The northern side of the mountains slopes more steeply to the sea and is the main coffee-producing area of the island, along with rice, vegetables, and cattle.
[src:bali/bali-p01] The longest river, Ayung River, flows approximately 75 km (47 mi) (see List of rivers of Bali).
[src:bali/bali-p01] The island is surrounded by coral reefs.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Beaches in the south tend to have white sand, while those in the north and west have black sand.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Bali has no major waterways, although the Ho River is navigable by small *sampan* boats.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Black sand beaches between Pasut and Klatingdukuh are being developed for tourism, but apart from the seaside temple of Tanah Lot, they are not yet used for significant tourism.
[src:bali/bali-p01] The largest city is the provincial capital, Denpasar, near the southern coast.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Bali's second-largest city is the old colonial capital, Singaraja, which is located on the north coast and whose urban area is home to around 150,000 people in 2024.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Other important cities include the beach resort, Kuta, which is practically part of Denpasar's urban area, and Ubud, situated at the north of Denpasar, which is regarded as the island's cultural centre.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Three small islands lie to the immediate south-east and all are administratively part of the Klungkung regency of Bali: Nusa Penida, Nusa Lembongan and Nusa Ceningan.
[src:bali/bali-p01] These islands are separated from Bali by the Badung Strait.
[src:bali/bali-p01] To the east, the Lombok Strait separates Bali from Lombok and marks the biogeographical division between the fauna of the Indomalayan realm and the distinctly different fauna of Australasia.
[src:bali/bali-p01] The transition is known as the Wallace Line, named after Alfred Russel Wallace, who first proposed a transition zone between these two major biomes.
[src:bali/bali-p01] When sea levels dropped during the Pleistocene ice age, Bali was connected to Java and Sumatra and to the mainland of Asia and shared the Asian fauna, but the deep water of the Lombok Strait continued to keep Lombok Island and the Lesser Sunda archipelago isolated.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Being just 8 degrees south of the equator, Bali has a fairly even climate all year round.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Average year-round temperature stands at around 30 °C (86 °F) with a humidity level of about 85%.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Daytime temperatures at low elevations vary between 20 and 33 °C (68 and 91 °F), but the temperatures decrease significantly with increasing elevation.
[src:bali/bali-p01] The west monsoon is in place from approximately October to April, and this can bring significant rain, particularly from December to March.
[src:bali/bali-p01] During the rainy season, there are comparatively fewer tourists seen in Bali.
[src:bali/bali-p01] During the Easter and Christmas holidays, the weather is very unpredictable.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Outside of the monsoon period, humidity is relatively low and any rain is unlikely in lowland areas.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Bali lies just to the west of the Wallace Line, and thus has a fauna that is Asian in character, with very little Australasian influence, and has more in common with Java than with Lombok.
[src:bali/bali-p01] An exception is the yellow-crested cockatoo, a member of a primarily Australasian family.
[src:bali/bali-p01] There are around 280 species of birds, including the critically endangered Bali myna, which is endemic.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Until the early 20th century, Bali was possibly home to several large mammals: banteng, leopard and the endemic Bali tiger.
[src:bali/bali-p01] The banteng still occurs in its domestic form, whereas leopards are found only in neighbouring Java, and the Bali tiger is extinct.
[src:bali/bali-p01] The last definite record of a tiger on Bali dates from 1937 when one was shot, though the subspecies may have survived until the 1940s or 1950s.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Pleistocene and Holocene megafaunas include banteng and giant tapir (based on speculations that they might have reached up to the Wallace Line), and rhinoceros.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Squirrels are quite commonly encountered, less often is the Asian palm civet, which is also kept in coffee farms to produce kopi luwak.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Bats are well represented, perhaps the most famous place to encounter them remaining is the Goa Lawah (Temple of the Bats) where they are worshipped by the locals and also constitute a tourist attraction.
[src:bali/bali-p01] They also occur in other cave temples, for instance at Gangga Beach.
[src:bali/bali-p01] The crab-eating macaque, known locally as "kera", is quite common around human settlements and temples, where it becomes accustomed to being fed by humans, particularly in any of the three "monkey forest" temples, such as the popular one in the Ubud area.
[src:bali/bali-p01] They are also quite often kept as pets by locals.
[src:bali/bali-p01] The second monkey, endemic to Java and some surrounding islands such as Bali, is far rarer and more elusive and is the Javan langur, locally known as "lutung".
[src:bali/bali-p01] They occur in a few places apart from the West Bali National Park.
[src:bali/bali-p01] They are born an orange colour, though they would have already changed to a more blackish colouration by their first year.
[src:bali/bali-p01] In Java, however, there is more of a tendency for this species to retain its juvenile orange colour into adulthood, and a mixture of black and orange monkeys can be seen together as a family.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Other rarer mammals include the Sunda leopard cat, Sunda pangolin and black giant squirrel.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Snakes include the king cobra and reticulated python.
[src:bali/bali-p01] The water monitor can grow to at least 1.5 m (4.9 ft) in length and 50 kg (110 lb) and can move quickly.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Dolphins are commonly encountered on the north coast near Singaraja and Lovina.
[src:bali/bali-p01] A team of scientists surveyed from 29 April 2011, to 11 May 2011, at 33 sea sites around Bali.
[src:bali/bali-p01] They discovered 952 species of reef fish of which 8 were new discoveries at Pemuteran, Gilimanuk, Nusa Dua, Tulamben and Candidasa, and 393 coral species, including two new ones at Padangbai and between Padangbai and Amed.
[src:bali/bali-p01] The average coverage level of healthy coral was 36% (better than in Raja Ampat and Halmahera by 29% or in Fakfak and Kaimana by 25%) with the highest coverage found in Gili Selang and Gili Mimpang in Candidasa, Karangasem Regency.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Among the larger trees the most common are: banyan trees, jackfruit, coconuts, bamboo species, acacia trees and also endless rows of coconuts and banana species.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Numerous flowers can be seen: hibiscus, frangipani, bougainvillea, poinsettia, oleander, jasmine, water lily, lotus, roses, begonias, orchids and hydrangeas exist.
[src:bali/bali-p01] On higher grounds that receive more moisture, for instance, around Kintamani, certain species of fern trees, mushrooms and even pine trees thrive well.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Other plants with agricultural value include: salak, mangosteen, corn, Kintamani orange, coffee and water spinach.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Over-exploitation by the tourist industry has led to 200 out of 400 rivers on the island drying up.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Research suggests that the southern part of Bali would face a water shortage.
[src:bali/bali-p01] To ease the shortage, the central government plans to build a water catchment and processing facility at Petanu River in Gianyar.
[src:bali/bali-p01] The 300 litres capacity of water per second will be channelled to Denpasar, Badung and Gianyar in 2013.
[src:bali/bali-p01] A 2010 Environment Ministry report on its environmental quality index gave Bali a score of 99.65, which was the highest score of Indonesia's 33 provinces.
[src:bali/bali-p01] The score considers the level of total suspended solids, dissolved oxygen, and chemical oxygen demand in water.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Erosion at Lebih Beach has seen seven metres (23 feet) of land lost every year.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Decades ago, this beach was used for holy pilgrimages with more than 10,000 people, but they have now moved to Masceti Beach.
[src:bali/bali-p01] In 2017, a year when Bali received nearly 5.7 million tourists, government officials declared a "garbage emergency" in response to the covering of 3.6-mile stretch of coastline in plastic waste brought in by the tide, amid concerns that the pollution could dissuade visitors from returning.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Indonesia is one of the world's worst plastic polluters, with some estimates suggesting the country is the source of around 10 per cent of the world's plastic waste.
[src:bali/bali-p01] On 3 February 2026, Bali launched a major beach clean up after President Prabowo Subianto's criticisms of the Bali's growing waste problem.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Hundreds of personnel from the Bali Police and the local military joined students and volunteers to collect rubbish from two of the island’s most popular tourist beaches: Kuta and Kedonganan in Badung Regency.
[src:bali/bali-p01] The governor is the highest officeholder in the Bali provincial government with the vice governor being the second highest officeholder.
[src:bali/bali-p01] The Governor of Bali is responsible for the territory of the Province of Bali.
[src:bali/bali-p01] The current governor in office in the province of Bali is I Wayan Koster who was first being elected in the 2018 Bali gubernatorial election accompanied by his first running mate at that time Tjokorda Oka Artha Ardana Sukawati (Cok Ace).
[src:bali/bali-p01] Koster is the 8th governor of Bali, since the province was formed into the province of Bali in 1958 based on Law Number 64 of 1958.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Koster and Cok Ace were inaugurated by the president of the Republic of Indonesia at that time Joko Widodo, at the State Palace, Jakarta on September 5, 2018, for the five years term of office (2018–2023).
[src:bali/bali-p01] After his term of office ended, Sang Made Mahendra Jaya was inaugurated as acting governor of Bali on September 5, 2023 with a limited authority in the government.
[src:bali/bali-p01] After re-elected in 2024 I Wayan Koster and I Nyoman Giri Prasta was inaugurated on February 20, 2025 at the State Palace by the incumbent President of Indonesia Prabowo Subianto for the five years term of office (2025–2030).
[src:bali/bali-p01] In the national legislature, Bali is represented by nine members, with a single electoral district covering the whole province.
[src:bali/bali-p01] The Bali Regional House of Representatives (DPRD), the provincial legislature, has 55 members.
[src:bali/bali-p01] The province's politics has historically been dominated by the Indonesian Democratic Party of Struggle (PDI-P), which has won by far the most votes in every election in Bali since the first free elections in 1999, it currently forms the ruling government in the province.
[src:bali/bali-p01] They are tabulated below with their areas and their populations at the 2010 census and the 2020 census, together with the official estimates as at mid 2024 and the Human Development Index for each regency and city.
[src:bali/bali-p01] The province forms one of Indonesia's 84 national electoral districts to elect members to the Indonesian parliament.
[src:bali/bali-p01] The **Bali Electoral District** consists of all of the 8 regencies in the province, together with the city of Denpasar, and elects 9 members to the People's Representative Council.
[src:bali/bali-p01] In the 1970s, the Balinese economy was largely agriculture-based in terms of both output and employment.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Tourism is now the largest single industry in terms of income, and as a result, Bali is one of Indonesia's wealthiest regions.
[src:bali/bali-p01] In 2003, around 80% of Bali's economy was tourism related.
[src:bali/bali-p01] By the end of June 2011, the rate of non-performing loans of all banks in Bali were 2.23%, lower than the average of Indonesian banking industry non-performing loan rates (about 5%).
[src:bali/bali-p01] The economy, however, suffered significantly as a result of the terrorist bombings in 2002 and 2005.
[src:bali/bali-p01] The tourism industry has since recovered from these events.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Although tourism produces the GDP's largest output, agriculture is still the island's biggest employer.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Fishing also provides a significant number of jobs.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Bali is also famous for its artisans who produce a vast array of handicrafts, including batik and ikat cloth and clothing, wooden carvings, stone carvings, painted art and silverware.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Notably, individual villages typically adopt a single product, such as wind chimes or wooden furniture.
[src:bali/bali-p01] The Arabica coffee production region is the highland region of Kintamani near Mount Batur.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Generally, Balinese coffee is processed using the wet method.
[src:bali/bali-p01] This results in a sweet, soft coffee with good consistency.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Typical flavours include lemon and other citrus notes.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Many coffee farmers in Kintamani are members of a traditional farming system called Subak Abian, which is based on the Hindu philosophy of "Tri Hita Karana".
[src:bali/bali-p01] According to this philosophy, the three causes of happiness are good relations with God, other people, and the environment.
[src:bali/bali-p01] The Subak Abian system is ideally suited to the production of fair trade and organic coffee production.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Arabica coffee from Kintamani is the first product in Indonesia to request a geographical indication.
[src:bali/bali-p01] In 2025, Bali received 6,948,754 international tourists, an increase of 9.72% compared to 2024..
[src:bali/bali-p01] In 1963, the Bali Beach Hotel in Sanur was built by Sukarno and boosted tourism in Bali.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Before the Bali Beach Hotel construction, there were only three significant tourist-class hotels on the island.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Construction of hotels and restaurants began to spread throughout Bali.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Tourism further increased in Bali after the Ngurah Rai International Airport opened in 1970.
[src:bali/bali-p01] The Buleleng regency government encouraged the tourism sector as one of the mainstays for economic progress and social welfare.
[src:bali/bali-p01] The tourism industry is primarily focused in the south, while also significant in the other parts of the island.
[src:bali/bali-p01] The United States government lifted its travel warnings in 2008.
[src:bali/bali-p01] The Australian government issued an advisory on Friday, 4 May 2012, with the overall level of this advisory lowered to 'Exercise a high degree of caution'.
[src:bali/bali-p01] The Swedish government issued a new warning on Sunday, 10 June 2012, because of one tourist who died from methanol poisoning.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Australia last issued an advisory on Monday, 5 January 2015, due to new terrorist threats.
[src:bali/bali-p01] An offshoot of tourism is the growing real estate industry.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Bali's real estate has been rapidly developing in the main tourist areas of Kuta, Legian, Seminyak, and Oberoi.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Most recently, high-end 5-star projects are under development on the Bukit peninsula, on the island's south side.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Expensive villas are being developed along the cliff sides of south Bali, with commanding panoramic ocean views.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Foreign and domestic, many Jakarta individuals and companies are fairly active, and investment into other areas of the island also continues to grow.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Land prices, despite the worldwide economic crisis, have remained stable.
[src:bali/bali-p01] In the last half of 2008, Indonesia's currency had dropped approximately 30% against the US dollar, providing many overseas visitors with improved value for their currencies.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Bali's tourism economy survived the terrorist bombings of 2002 and 2005, and the tourism industry has slowly recovered and surpassed its pre-terrorist bombing levels; the long-term trend has been a steady increase in visitor arrivals.
[src:bali/bali-p01] In 2010, Bali received 2.57 million foreign tourists, which surpassed the target of 2.0–2.3 million tourists.
[src:bali/bali-p01] The average occupancy of starred hotels achieved 65%, so the island still should be able to accommodate tourists for some years without any addition of new rooms/hotels, although at the peak season some of them are fully booked.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Bali received the Best Island award from Travel and Leisure in 2010.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Bali won because of its attractive surroundings (both mountain and coastal areas), diverse tourist attractions, excellent international and local restaurants, and the friendliness of the local people.
[src:bali/bali-p01] The Balinese culture and its religion are also considered the main factor of the award.
[src:bali/bali-p01] One of the most prestigious events that symbolize a strong relationship between a god and its followers is Kecak dance.
[src:bali/bali-p01] According to BBC Travel released in 2011, Bali is one of the World's Best Islands, ranking second after Santorini, Greece.
[src:bali/bali-p01] In 2006, Elizabeth Gilbert's memoir *Eat, Pray, Love* was published, and in August 2010 it was adapted into the film *Eat Pray Love*.
[src:bali/bali-p01] It took place at Ubud and Padang-Padang Beach in Bali.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Both the book and the film fuelled a boom in tourism in Ubud, the hill town and cultural and tourist centre that was the focus of Gilbert's quest for balance and love through traditional spirituality and healing.
[src:bali/bali-p01] In January 2016, after musician David Bowie died, it was revealed that in his will, Bowie asked for his ashes to be scattered in Bali, conforming to Buddhist rituals.
[src:bali/bali-p01] He had visited and performed in several Southeast Asian cities early in his career, including Bangkok and Singapore.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Since 2011, China has displaced Japan as the second-largest supplier of tourists to Bali, while Australia still tops the list while India has also emerged as a greater supplier of tourists.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Chinese tourists increased by 17% in 2011 from 2010 due to the impact of ACFTA and new direct flights to Bali.
[src:bali/bali-p01] In January 2012, Chinese tourists increased by 222.18% compared to January 2011, while Japanese tourists declined by 23.54% year on year.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Bali is a very popular tourist destination for Indians.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Bali authorities reported the island had 2.88 million foreign tourists and 5 million domestic tourists in 2012, marginally surpassing the expectations of 2.8 million foreign tourists.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Based on a Bank Indonesia survey in May 2013, 34.39 per cent of tourists are upper-middle class, spending between $1,286 and $5,592, and are dominated by Australia, India, France, China, Germany and the UK.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Some Chinese tourists have increased their levels of spending from previous years.
[src:bali/bali-p01] 30.26 per cent of tourists are middle class, spending between $662 and $1,285.
[src:bali/bali-p01] In 2017 it was expected that Chinese tourists would outnumber Australian tourists.
[src:bali/bali-p01] In January 2020, 10,000 Chinese tourists cancelled trips to Bali due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Because of the COVID-19 pandemic travel restrictions, Bali welcomed 1.07 million international travelers in 2020, most of them between January and March, which is −87% compared to 2019.
[src:bali/bali-p01] In the first half of 2021, they welcomed 43 international travelers.
[src:bali/bali-p01] The pandemic presented a major blow on Bali's tourism-dependent economy.
[src:bali/bali-p01] On 3 February 2022, Bali reopened again for the first foreign tourists after 2 years of being closed due to the pandemic.
[src:bali/bali-p01] In 2022 Indonesia's Minister of Health, Budi Sadikin, stated that the tourism industry in Bali will be complemented by the medical industry.
[src:bali/bali-p01] At the beginning of 2023, the governor of Bali demanded a ban on the use of motorcycles by tourists.
[src:bali/bali-p01] This happened after a series of accidents.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Wayan Koster proposed to cancel the violators' visas.
[src:bali/bali-p01] The move sparked widespread outrage on social media.
[src:bali/bali-p01] The Ngurah Rai International Airport is located near Jimbaran, on the isthmus at the southernmost part of the island.
[src:bali/bali-p01] A coastal road circles the island, and three major two-lane arteries cross the central mountains at passes reaching 1,750 m in height (at Penelokan).
[src:bali/bali-p01] The Ngurah Rai Bypass is a four-lane expressway that partly encircles Denpasar.
[src:bali/bali-p01] There is a car ferry between Gilimanuk on the west coast of Bali to Ketapang on Java which started running in the 1930s.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Two bus systems exist: Trans Sarbagita and Trans Metro Dewata.
[src:bali/bali-p01] In December 2010 the Government of Indonesia invited investors to build a new Tanah Ampo Cruise Terminal at Karangasem, Bali with a projected worth of $30 million.
[src:bali/bali-p01] On 17 July 2011, the first cruise ship (Sun Princess) anchored about 400 metres (1,300 feet) away from the wharf of Tanah Ampo harbour.
[src:bali/bali-p01] The current pier is only 154 metres (505 feet) but will eventually be extended to 300 to 350 metres (980–1,150 feet) to accommodate international cruise ships.
[src:bali/bali-p01] The harbour is safer than the existing facility at Benoa and has a scenic backdrop of east Bali mountains and green rice fields.
[src:bali/bali-p01] The tender for improvement was subject to delays, and as of July 2013 the situation was unclear with cruise line operators complaining and even refusing to use the existing facility at Tanah Ampo.
[src:bali/bali-p01] A memorandum of understanding was signed by two ministers, Bali's governor and Indonesian Train Company to build 565 kilometres (351 miles) of railway along the coast around the island.
[src:bali/bali-p01] As of July 2015, no details of these proposed railways have been released.
[src:bali/bali-p01] In 2019 it was reported in *Gapura Bali* that Wayan Koster, governor of Bali, "is keen to improve Bali's transportation infrastructure and is considering plans to build an electric rail network across the island".
[src:bali/bali-p01] On 16 March 2011 (Tanjung) Benoa port received the "Best Port Welcome 2010" award from London's "Dream World Cruise Destination" magazine.
[src:bali/bali-p01] Government plans to expand the role of Benoa port as export-import port to boost Bali's trade and industry sector.
[src:bali/bali-p01] In 2013, The Tourism and Creative Economy Ministry advised that 306 cruise liners were scheduled to visit Indonesia, an increase of 43 per cent compared to the previous year.
[src:bali/bali-p01] In May 2011, an integrated Area Traffic Control System (ATCS) was implemented to reduce traffic jams at four crossing points: Ngurah Rai statue, Dewa Ruci Kuta crossing, Jimbaran crossing and Sanur crossing.
[src:bali/bali-p01] ATCS is an integrated system connecting all traffic lights, CCTVs and other traffic signals with a monitoring office at the police headquarters.
[src:bali/bali-p01] It has successfully been implemented in other ASEAN countries and will be implemented at other crossings in Bali.
[src:bali/bali-p01] On 21 December 2011, construction started on the Nusa Dua-Benoa-Ngurah Rai International Airport toll road, which will also provide a special lane for motorcycles.
[src:bali/bali-p01] This has been done by seven state-owned enterprises led by PT Jasa Marga with 60% of the shares.
[src:bali/bali-p01] PT Jasa Marga Bali Tol will construct the 9.91-kilometre-long (6.16-mile) toll road (totally 12.7 kilometres (7.89 miles) with access road).
[src:bali/bali-p01] The construction is estimated to cost Rp.2.49 trillion ($273.9 million).
[src:bali/bali-p01] The project goes through 2 kilometres (1 mile) of mangrove forest and through 2.3 kilometres (1.4 miles) of beach, both within 5.4 hectares (13 acres) area.
[src:bali/bali-p01] The elevated toll road is built over the mangrove forest on 18,000 concrete pillars that occupied two hectares of mangrove forest.
[src:bali/bali-p01] This was compensated by the planting of 300,000 mangrove trees along the road.
[src:bali/bali-p01] On 21 December 2011, the Dewa Ruci 450-metre (1,480-foot) underpass has also started on the busy Dewa Ruci junction near Bali Kuta Galeria with an estimated cost of Rp136 billion ($14.9 million) from the state budget.
[src:bali/bali-p01] On 23 September 2013, the Bali Mandara Toll Road was opened, with the Dewa Ruci Junction underpass being opened previously.
[src:bali/bali-p01] To solve chronic traffic problems, the province will also build a toll road connecting Serangan with Tohpati, a toll road connecting Kuta, Denpasar, and Tohpati, and a flyover connecting Kuta and Ngurah Rai Airport.
[src:bali/bali-p02] In 2021, the Indonesian Ministry of Tourism estimated that there were 109,801 foreigners living on Bali, with most originating from Russia, United States, Australia, United Kingdom, Germany, Japan, France, Italy, India, and the Netherlands.
[src:bali/bali-p02] A DNA study in 2005 by Karafet et al., found that 84% of Balinese Y-chromosomes are of likely Austronesian origin, 12% of likely Indian origin and 2% of likely Melanesian origin.
[src:bali/bali-p02] According to a recent genetic study, the Balinese, together with the Javanese and Sundanese, have a significant admixture of Austroasiatic and Austronesian ancestries.
[src:bali/bali-p02] The majority of the population inhabiting the province of Bali are the local ethnic, namely the Balinese and indigenous Bali Aga people.
[src:bali/bali-p02] The Balinese have a cultural richness that is known worldwide, so that Bali is the main destination for foreign tourists to Indonesia.
[src:bali/bali-p02] In addition to the rich beaches, the culture that is of interest in Bali is its dances, such as the Kecak dance, festivals such as Ogoh-ogoh, and others.
[src:bali/bali-p02] The largest ethnic group outside the Balinese people is the Javanese people.
[src:bali/bali-p02] Pre-modern Bali had four castes, but with a "very strong tradition of communal decision-making and interdependence".
[src:bali/bali-p02] The four castes have been classified as Sudra (Shudra), Wesia (Vaishyas), Satria (Kshatriyas) and Brahmana (Brahmin).
[src:bali/bali-p02] In Bali, the Shudra (locally spelt *Soedra*) has typically been the temple priests, though depending on the demographics, a temple priest may also be from the other three castes.
[src:bali/bali-p02] In most regions, it has been the Shudra who typically make offerings to the gods on behalf of the Hindu devotees, chant prayers, recite *meweda* (Vedas), and set the course of Balinese temple festivals.
[src:bali/bali-p02] About 86.40% of Bali's population adheres to Balinese Hinduism, formed as a combination of existing local beliefs and Hindu beliefs from mainland Southeast Asia and South Asia.
[src:bali/bali-p02] The Balinese people and Bali Aga are generally Hindu with some being Muslim (3.24%) and Christian (1.26%).
[src:bali/bali-p02] The Javanese, Sundanese, Sasak, and Malay people are generally Muslim and some are also Hindu or Christian.
[src:bali/bali-p02] Meanwhile, people from East Nusa Tenggara, as well as people of the Papua, Batak, Chinese and some other Indonesian ethnic groups that aren't traditionally Muslim are generally Christian, with small minority are Hindu and Muslim.
[src:bali/bali-p02] The village of Blimbing Sari in the Melaya district of Jembrana Regency, not far from Gilimanuk Port, is Christian, and the residents there are native Balinese, but the church is shaped like a Hindu temple.
[src:bali/bali-p02] The general beliefs and practices of *Agama Hindu Dharma* mix ancient traditions and contemporary pressures placed by Indonesian laws that permit only monotheist belief under the national ideology of *Pancasila*.
[src:bali/bali-p02] Traditionally, Hinduism in Indonesia had a pantheon of deities and that tradition of belief continues in practice; further, Hinduism in Indonesia granted freedom and flexibility to Hindus as to when, how and where to pray.
[src:bali/bali-p02] However, officially, the Indonesian government considers and advertises Indonesian Hinduism as a monotheistic religion with certain officially recognised beliefs that comply with its national ideology.
[src:bali/bali-p02] Indonesian school textbooks describe Hinduism as having one supreme being, Hindus offering three daily mandatory prayers, and Hinduism as having certain common beliefs that in part parallel those of Islam.
[src:bali/bali-p02] Some scholars contest whether these Indonesian government recognised and assigned beliefs to reflect the traditional beliefs and practices of Hindus in Indonesia before Indonesia gained independence from Dutch colonial rule.
[src:bali/bali-p02] Balinese Hinduism has roots in Indian Hinduism and Buddhism, which arrived through Java.
[src:bali/bali-p02] Hindu influences reached the Indonesian Archipelago as early as the first century.
[src:bali/bali-p02] Historical evidence is unclear about the diffusion process of cultural and spiritual ideas from India.
[src:bali/bali-p02] Java legends refer to Saka-era, traced to 78 AD.
[src:bali/bali-p02] Stories from the Mahabharata Epic have been traced in Indonesian islands to the 1st century; however, the versions mirror those found in the southeast Indian peninsular region (now Tamil Nadu and southern Karnataka and Andhra Pradesh).
[src:bali/bali-p02] The Bali tradition adopted the pre-existing animistic traditions of the indigenous people.
[src:bali/bali-p02] This influence strengthened the belief that the gods and goddesses are present in all things.
[src:bali/bali-p02] Every element of nature, therefore, possesses its power, which reflects the power of the gods.
[src:bali/bali-p02] A rock, tree, dagger, or woven cloth is a potential home for spirits whose energy can be directed for good or evil.
[src:bali/bali-p02] Balinese Hinduism is deeply interwoven with art and ritual.
[src:bali/bali-p02] Ritualising states of self-control are a notable feature of religious expression among the people, who for this reason have become famous for their graceful and decorous behavior.
[src:bali/bali-p02] Apart from the majority of Balinese Hindus, there also exist Chinese immigrants whose traditions have melded with that of the locals.
[src:bali/bali-p02] As a result, these Sino-Balinese embrace their original religion, which is a mixture of Buddhism, Christianity, Taoism, and Confucianism, and find a way to harmonise it with the local traditions.
[src:bali/bali-p02] Hence, it is not uncommon to find local Sino-Balinese during the local temple's *odalan*.
[src:bali/bali-p02] Moreover, Balinese Hindu priests are invited to perform rites alongside a Chinese priest in the event of the death of a Sino-Balinese.
[src:bali/bali-p02] Nevertheless, the Sino-Balinese claim to embrace Buddhism for administrative purposes, such as their Identity Cards.
[src:bali/bali-p02] The Roman Catholic community has a diocese, the Diocese of Denpasar that encompasses the province of Bali and West Nusa Tenggara and has its cathedral located in Denpasar.
[src:bali/bali-p02] Balinese and Indonesian are the most widely spoken languages in Bali, and the vast majority of Balinese people are bilingual or trilingual.
[src:bali/bali-p02] The most common spoken language around the tourist areas is Indonesian, as many people in the tourist sector are not solely Balinese, but migrants from Java, Lombok, Sumatra, and other parts of Indonesia.
[src:bali/bali-p02] The Balinese language is heavily stratified due to the Balinese caste system.
[src:bali/bali-p02] Kawi and Sanskrit are also commonly used by some Hindu priests in Bali, as Hindu literature was mostly written in Sanskrit.
[src:bali/bali-p02] English and Chinese are the next most common languages (and the primary foreign languages) of many Balinese, owing to the requirements of the tourism industry, as well as the English-speaking community and huge Chinese-Indonesian population.
[src:bali/bali-p02] Other foreign languages, such as Japanese, Korean, French, Russian or German, are often used in multilingual signs for foreign tourists.
[src:bali/bali-p02] Bali is renowned for its diverse and sophisticated art forms, such as painting, sculpture, woodcarving, handcrafts, and performing arts.
[src:bali/bali-p02] Balinese cuisine is also distinctive, and unlike the rest of Indonesia, pork is commonly found in Balinese dishes such as Babi Guling.
[src:bali/bali-p02] Balinese percussion orchestra music, known as *gamelan*, is highly developed and varied.
[src:bali/bali-p02] Balinese performing arts often portray stories from Hindu epics such as the Ramayana but with heavy Balinese influence.
[src:bali/bali-p02] Famous Balinese dances include *pendet*, *legong*, *baris*, *topeng*, *barong*, *gong kebyar*, and *kecak* (the monkey dance).
[src:bali/bali-p02] Bali boasts one of the most diverse and innovative performing arts cultures in the world, with paid performances at thousands of temple festivals, private ceremonies, and public shows.
[src:bali/bali-p02] In 2018 Governor I Wayan Koster issued Bali Governor's Regulation No.
[src:bali/bali-p02] 79 of 2018 which mandated that city officials wear traditional Balinese dress, such as that made of *songket*.
[src:bali/bali-p02] 4 of 2021 which specified the use of Endek fabrics, and was expanded to high-ranking individuals in the private sector and other institutions.
[src:bali/bali-p02] Most temples have an inner courtyard and an outer courtyard which are arranged with the inner courtyard furthest *kaja*.
[src:bali/bali-p02] These spaces serve as performance venues since most Balinese rituals are accompanied by any combination of music, dance, and drama.
[src:bali/bali-p02] The performances that take place in the inner courtyard are classified as *wali*, the most sacred rituals which are offerings exclusively for the gods, while the outer courtyard is where *bebali* ceremonies are held, which are intended for gods and people.
[src:bali/bali-p02] Lastly, performances meant solely for the entertainment of humans take place outside the temple's walls and are called *bali-balihan*.
[src:bali/bali-p02] This three-tiered system of classification was standardised in 1971 by a committee of Balinese officials and artists to better protect the sanctity of the oldest and most sacred Balinese rituals from being performed for a paying audience.
[src:bali/bali-p02] Tourism, Bali's chief industry, has provided the island with a foreign audience that is eager to pay for entertainment, thus creating new performance opportunities and more demand for performers.
[src:bali/bali-p02] The impact of tourism is controversial since before it became integrated into the economy, the Balinese performing arts did not exist as a capitalist venture, and were not performed for entertainment outside of their respective ritual context.
[src:bali/bali-p02] Since the 1930s sacred rituals such as the *barong* dance have been performed both in their original contexts, as well as exclusively for paying tourists.
[src:bali/bali-p02] This has led to new versions of many of these performances that have developed according to the preferences of foreign audiences; some villages have a *barong* mask specifically for non-ritual performances and an older mask that is only used for sacred performances.
[src:bali/bali-p02] Throughout the year, there are many festivals celebrated locally or island-wide according to the traditional calendars.
[src:bali/bali-p02] The Hindu New Year, *Nyepi*, is celebrated in the spring by a day of silence.
[src:bali/bali-p02] On this day everyone stays at home and tourists are encouraged (or required) to remain in their hotels.
[src:bali/bali-p02] On the day before New Year, large and colourful sculptures of *Ogoh-ogoh* monsters are paraded and burned in the evening to drive away evil spirits.
[src:bali/bali-p02] Other festivals throughout the year are specified by the Balinese *pawukon* calendrical system.
[src:bali/bali-p02] Celebrations are held for many occasions such as a tooth-filing (coming-of-age ritual), cremation or *odalan* (temple festival).
[src:bali/bali-p02] One of the most important concepts that Balinese ceremonies have in common is that of *désa kala patra*, which refers to how ritual performances must be appropriate in both the specific and general social context.
[src:bali/bali-p02] Many ceremonial art forms such as *wayang kulit* and *topeng* are highly improvisatory, providing flexibility for the performer to adapt the performance to the current situation.
[src:bali/bali-p02] Many celebrations call for a loud, boisterous atmosphere with much activity, and the resulting aesthetic, *ramé*, is distinctively Balinese.
[src:bali/bali-p02] Often two or more *gamelan* ensembles will be performing well within earshot, and sometimes compete with each other to be heard.
[src:bali/bali-p02] Likewise, the audience members talk amongst themselves, get up and walk around, or even cheer on the performance, which adds to the many layers of activity and the liveliness typical of *ramé*.
[src:bali/bali-p02] Balinese society continues to revolve around each family's ancestral village, to which the cycle of life and religion is closely tied.
[src:bali/bali-p02] Coercive aspects of traditional society, such as customary law sanctions imposed by traditional authorities such as village councils (including "kasepekang", or shunning) have risen in importance as a consequence of the democratisation and decentralisation of Indonesia since 1998.
[src:bali/bali-p02] Other than Balinese sacred rituals and festivals, the government presents Bali Arts Festival to showcase Bali's performing arts and various artworks produced by the local talents that they have.
[src:bali/bali-p02] It is held once a year, from the second week of June until the end of July.
[src:bali/bali-p02] Southeast Asia's biggest annual festival of words and ideas Ubud Writers and Readers Festival is held at Ubud in October, which is participated by the world's most celebrated writers, artists, thinkers, and performers.
[src:bali/bali-p02] One unusual tradition is the naming of children in Bali.
[src:bali/bali-p02] In general, Balinese people name their children depending on the order they are born, and the names are the same for both males and females.
[src:bali/bali-p02] Bali was the host of Miss World 2013 (63rd edition of the Miss World pageant).
[src:bali/bali-p02] It was the first time Indonesia hosted an international beauty pageant.
[src:bali/bali-p02] In 2022, Bali also co-hosted Miss Grand International 2022 along with Jakarta, West Java, and Banten.
[src:bali/bali-p02] Bali has hosted several milestone regional and sectoral gatherings, including foundational ASEAN summits.
[src:bali/bali-p02] Key agreements signed on the island include the 1976 Declaration of ASEAN Concord and the Treaty of Amity and Cooperation in Southeast Asia, as well as the Bali Concord II (2003) and Bali Concord III (2011).
[src:bali/bali-p02] It also serves as the venue for the East Asia Summit's "Bali Principles" for mutually beneficial relations.
[src:bali/bali-p02] The province has been a focal point for global environmental and trade governance.
[src:bali/bali-p02] It hosted the 2007 UNFCCC COP13, which produced the Bali Road Map, and the 2013 APEC Leaders' Week.
[src:bali/bali-p02] Additionally, the WTO Ninth Ministerial Conference adopted the "Bali Package" on trade facilitation in 2013.
[src:bali/bali-p02] Bali also anchors regional governance architectures through recurring platforms like the Bali Process on people smuggling and the Bali Democracy Forum.
[src:bali/bali-p02] In 2022, the UN’s Global Platform for Disaster Risk Reduction was held on the island.
[src:bali/bali-p02] More recently, Bali has hosted the Multilateral Naval Exercise Komodo (MNEK).
[src:bali/bali-p02] The 2025 iteration involved 38 countries and 19 foreign warships at Tanjung Benoa.
[src:bali/bali-p02] These drills occurred amid regional tensions in the South China Sea regarding maritime claims, including China's "nine-dash line" which a 2016 arbitral tribunal under UNCLOS found had no legal basis.
[src:bali/bali-p02] Bali is a major world surfing destination with popular breaks dotted across the southern coastline and around the offshore island of Nusa Lembongan.
[src:bali/bali-p02] As part of the Coral Triangle, Bali, including Nusa Penida, offers a wide range of dive sites with varying types of reefs, and tropical aquatic life.
[src:bali/bali-p02] Bali was the host of 2008 Asian Beach Games.
[src:bali/bali-p02] It was the second time Indonesia hosted an Asia-level multi-sport event, after Jakarta held the 1962 Asian Games.
[src:bali/bali-p02] In 2023, Bali was the location for a major eSports event, the Dota 2 Bali Major, the third and final Major of the Dota Pro Circuit season.
[src:bali/bali-p02] The event was held at the Ayana Estate and the Champa Garden, and it was the first time that a Dota Pro Circuit Major was held in Indonesia.
[src:bali/bali-p02] In football, Bali is home to Bali United football club, which plays in Liga 1.
[src:bali/bali-p02] The team was relocated from Samarinda, East Kalimantan to Gianyar, Bali.
[src:bali/bali-p02] Harbiansyah Hanafiah, the main commissioner of Bali United explained that he changed the name and moved the home base because there was no representative from Bali in the highest football tier in Indonesia.
[src:bali/bali-p02] Another reason was due to local fans in Samarinda preferring to support Pusamania Borneo F.C. rather than Persisam.
[src:bali/bali-p02] In June 2012, Subak, the irrigation system for paddy fields in Jatiluwih, central Bali was listed as a Natural UNESCO World Heritage Site.
